[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Always sacrifice the exchange!"]
[ChapterName "A common Sicilian exchange sacrifice"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/WnmImhnb"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/1b1nbppp/p2p1n2/1p2pP2/4P3/PNNQB3/1PP1B1PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.11.29"]
[UTCTime "06:12:13"]

{ This position is from a Sicilian Najdorf, although this setup can occur from many Sicilians. With so much pressure on e4 and the c3 knight being the key defender, this exchange sacrifice should come as no surprise! }
1... Rxc3 2. Qxc3 (2. bxc3 Bxe4 3. Qd2 Nb6 $19 { A worse version of the game. } { [%cal Gb6c4] }) 2... Bxe4 { White: 👍up the exchange, 👍good pawn structure, 👎down a central pawn, 👎potential weakness on c2. Black: 👍incredible bishop on e4, 👍two central pawns and d5 cannot be stopped, 👍up a pawn, 👍no pawn weaknesses. More nuanced than last position, but black has incredible compensation! } 3. Nd2 Nd5! (3... Bb7 4. Rad1 Qa8 $17 { Even if black doesn't see Nd5 winning the bishop pair, black has extremely active pieces and retains the central pawn majority. Black remains better. }) 4. Qb3 Nxe3 5. Qxe3 Bb7 $17 { Black finds a way to deprive white of the bishop pair too! After Bg5 and Nc5, it is clear that all of black's pieces are more active than white's. The "extra rook" white has is stuck on a1 still doing nothing. Black is down 1 point of material, but engine says -1 purely because of positional compensation! } { [%cal Ge7g5,Gd7c5] } *


