[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Feel free to skip to move 13 if you just want to analyze the exchange sacrifice. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. Be3 exd4 8. Nxd4 Re8 9. f3 c6 10. Qd2 d5 11. exd5 cxd5 12. O-O Nc6 13. c5!? { White wants to push his queenside majority after Rab1 and b4-b5. } 13... Rxe3! 14. Qxe3 Qf8! { [%cal Gf8c5] } 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Kh1 Rb8 { All of black's pieces are active. While Kasparov does not have full compensation for the exchange because white is extremely solid as well, white has to take care to avoid black's queenside counterplay from walking over him while he's not fully coordinated. } 17. Na4! { [%cal Ga4b2,Ga4c5] } 17... Rb4 18. b3 Be6 19. Nb2 (19. Rad1!? { White can keep a slight advantage here, but it remains tricky: } 19... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5,Gf8c5] } 20. Bd3 Rh4 21. Qg5 Rh5 22. Qg3 { Black is winning on all sides of the board, but white can give up a pawn to maintain coordination. } 22... Nxc5 23. Nxc5 Qxc5 $14) 19... Nh5! $10 { Black's uncontested dark squared bishop rules the board. White has to remain vigilant to avoid being worse. } 20. Nd3 Rh4 21. Qf2 Qe7 22. g4 Bd4! 23. Qxd4 Rxh2+ 24. Kxh2 Qh4+ $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Repetition was unavoidable. } { [%cal Gh2g1,Gg1h2,Gh4g3,Gg3h4] } 1/2-1/2


[Event "1966 World Chess Championship"]
[Date "1966"]
[White "Tigran Petrosian"]
[Black "Boris Spassky"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Always sacrifice the exchange!"]
[ChapterName "Petrosian - Spassky, 1966"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/fdC1C5FF"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/7p/p2p4/nppPn3/2P2P2/1P5b/PQ1NB2P/R2N1RK1 w - - 1 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

21. Ne3! { Always sacrifice the exchange! } (21. Rf2? Rxf4! 22. Rxf4 Qg5+ $19 { [%cal Gg5f4,Gg5g1] }) 21... Bxf1 (21... Rxf4 22. Rxf4 Qg5+ 23. Rg4 Nxg4 24. Nxg4 Bxg4 25. Bxg4 Qxg4+ 26. Kh1 Qd4 $10 { Best play by both sides. After Qd4, black is on the worse side of equal, but almost certainly drawing the game. }) 22. Rxf1 Ng6 23. Bg4! Nxf4?? 24. Rxf4! { ALWAYS sacrifice the exchange! } 24... Rxf4 25. Be6+ { White has sacrificed two exchanges, but has an amazing bishop on e6, a dominant queen controlling the long diagonal, and two knights that are ready to spin into the attack! Black's a5 knight and a1 rook are irrelevant to the position... } 25... Rf7 26. Ne4 { [%csl Gg5,Gd6] } (26. Bxf7+?? $10 { The bishop is clearly stronger than the pinned rook! }) 26... Qh4 27. Nxd6 { This position is now hopeless, but Spassky tries to give himself chances for a perpetual check. } { [%csl Gf7] } 27... Qg5+ (27... Ra7 28. Nef5 $18 { [%cal Gb2g7] }) 28. Kh1 Ra7 (28... Qxe3?? 29. Bxf7+ Kf8 30. Qh8+ Ke7 31. Nf5+ Kxf7 32. Qg7+ Ke8 33. Nxe3 $18 { A crucial variation that Spassky might not have fully seen from a distance. }) 29. Bxf7+ Rxf7 30. Qh8+! $18 { Black resigned rather than face the following variation: } 30... Kxh8 31. Nxf7+ Kg7 32. Nxg5 $18 *


[Event "Always sacrifice the exchange!: Kramnik - Bluebaum, 2017"]
[Date "2017"]
[White "Vladimir Kramnik"]
[Black "Matthias Bluebaum"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Always sacrifice the exchange!"]
[ChapterName "Kramnik - Bluebaum, 2017"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/plYMsbbt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r3nrk1/pp1q1pp1/1b2p1b1/3pB1Pp/3P1P2/1QN4P/PP2P1B1/2R2RK1 w - - 1 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Vladimir Kramnik, here as white, is clearly attacking black on the kingside. The issue is that black smartly played h5 earlier, preventing the idea of g4+f5 to break down the kingside. Kramnik comes up with an alternative way to open up the kingside. }
19. f5! Bxf5 20. Rxf5 exf5 21. Nxd5 { White is down a full exchange, but importantly has also opened up the a2-g8 diagonal towards black's king. The active d5 knight and kingside prospects give white full compensation, but not much more than that. } 21... Qe6! { Pressuring d5 stops white from playing Qg3 and continuing the kingside assault. } 22. Kh1 Rd8 23. Qf3 g6 24. e3?! (24. Nxb6!? axb6 25. Qxb7 $14 { Kramnik probably did not play this because he liked his central knight so much, but if you evaluate this position closely, it's clear the bishop pair and extra pawn more than compensate for the exchange. }) 24... Kh7?! (24... Rd7! $15 { Might have barely put a cap on white's kingside activity by defending the 7th rank. Even here though, white has near full compensation. }) 25. Nf4 Qe7 26. Qg3 Bc7 27. Rxc7! { Our bishop on e5 is much stronger than either rook. Keeping the bishop pair allows Kramnik to continue the kingside attack unabated! } 27... Nxc7 28. Bf6 Qb4 29. Nxh5! (29. Bxd8?? Rxd8 $19 { We are not interested in winning back material! }) 29... gxh5 30. g6+! Kg8 (30... fxg6?? 31. Qxc7+ $18) 31. Qg5 h4?? (31... Nd5! { Barely held together black's position but black has to give up the d8 rook and a lot of their material advantage. } 32. Bxd8 Qd6 33. gxf7+ Kxf7 34. Qxh5+ Kg7 35. Bh4 $14) 32. Qh6 { [%cal Gh6g7] } 32... Qe1+ 33. Kh2 Qg3+ 34. Kg1 Qe1+ 35. Bf1! $18 { With no more checks after the following potential sequence, black resigned. } 35... Qg3+!? (35... Qxe3+?! { The only way to avoid mate hangs a full queen. } 36. Qxe3 $18) 36. Kh1 Qf3+ 37. Bg2 Qd1+ 38. Kh2 $18 { Qg7# is unstoppable. } *


[Event "Always sacrifice the exchange!: Duda - Carlsen, 2020"]
[Date "2020"]
[White "Jan-Krzysztof Duda"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
