[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1rbb4/2qn1kpp/p1p1p3/P1Pp1p2/3P4/Q1BNP3/1R3PPP/3B2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.11.29"]
[UTCTime "06:12:13"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In this tense battle between Steinitz and Chigorin from 1892, white has a great position. But how can we break through? }
1. Rb6! Nxb6 { At this point we should appreciate that taking the rook is positionally suicidal. But even if was not taken, the rook on b6 forever attacks both fixed weaknesses: a6 and c6. } 2. cxb6! (2. axb6? { Not the correct recapture! The a5 square is meaningless, but the c5 square could potentially end the game! } 2... Qb7 3. Ne5+ Kg8 4. Qa4 Bd7 $14) 2... Qb7 3. Ne5+ (3. Nc5?! { Tempting, and certainly not giving up the advantage, but black had a trick up their sleeve against this move: Be7! } 3... Be7! $16) (3. Ba4! $18 { Also a great move. First play Ne5+ for the solution. }) (3. Bb4! $18 { Also a good move. The solution I had in mind went directly after the newly weakened c6 pawn. }) 3... Kg8 4. Ba4 $18 { White's position is clearly dominant. White will calmly attack c6, remove the b7 blockader of the passed b pawn, and get a new queen. Steinitz went on to win this game. } { [%csl Gc6] } *


